  "prompt": "How do you determine the Lewis structure of SO2?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082), follow these steps:\n\n1. **Count Valence Electrons:**\n   - Sulfur (S) has 6 valence electrons.\n   - Oxygen (O) also has 6 valence electrons.\n   - For SO\u2082, the total number of valence electrons is \\(1 \\times 6 \\, (\\text{for S}) + 2 \\times 6 \\, (\\text{for each O}) = 18\\) valence electrons.\n\n2. **Choose the Central Atom:**\n   - The central atom is typically the least electronegative one that isn't hydrogen. In this case, sulfur (S) is the central atom.\n\n3. **Sketch a Skeleton Structure:**\n   - Connect the two oxygen atoms to the central sulfur atom with single bonds initially:  \n\n     O \u2014 S \u2014 O\n\n4. **Distribute Electrons to Complete Octets:**\n   - First, fulfill the octets of the oxygen atoms by adding pairs of electrons to them. Each oxygen needs 8 electrons (including those in bonds), subtracting those used in bonds:\n\n     \\[\n     \\begin{array}{c}\n     \\text{O: 1 bond (2 electrons) + 6 non-bonding electrons = 8 electrons} \\\\\n     \\text{O: 1 bond (2 electrons) + 6 non-bonding electrons = 8 electrons} \\\\\n     \\end{array}\n     \\]\n\n   - This setup uses up 12 valence electrons for the lone pairs on oxygen atoms (6 on each oxygen) and 4 electrons in the S-O bonds, totaling 16. Therefore, 2 valence electrons are left to place on the sulfur atom.\n\n5. **Complete the Octet of the Central Atom:**\n   - Place the remaining 2 electrons on the sulfur atom to start completing its octet.\n   - At this point, sulfur has 6 electrons (2 lone pair electrons + 2 for each S-O bond (double bonds in total)). \n\n6. **Form Double Bonds if Necessary:**\n   - Adjust the structure to fulfill the octet rule for each atom. In the correct structure, sulfur will form double bonds with each oxygen to satisfy its octet:\n\n     \\[\n     \\begin{array}{c}\n     \\text{O} = \\text{S} = \\text{O} \\\\\n     \\end{array}\n     \\]\n\n   - Now, both oxygen atoms and the sulfur atom have complete octets.\n\n7. **Check Formal Charges:**\n   - Calculate formal charges to ensure the most stable structure:\n     - For oxygen with 6 electrons around it (1 lone pair + 1 in a double bond): Formal charge = 6 - (4 + 2/2) = 0\n     - For sulfur with 6 electrons around it (in 2 double bonds): Formal charge = 6 - (4 + 4/2) = 0\n\nThe stable Lewis structure for SO\u2082 is therefore as represented above, with double bonds between sulfur and each oxygen atom. This configuration minimizes formal charges across the molecule, giving a more stable structure.",
